al work for us — boilers, large-volume water heaters, restaurant plumbing, hotel hot water plant work, and the steam units still running in older buildings around the central business district. We've worked downtown buildings for five generations, which means when a 1920s office building has a steam unit nobody else wants to touch, we usually have parts on the truck or know exactly where to source them."}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"lg:col-span-5","children":["$","$Le",null,{}]}]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"py-16 lg:py-24","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"eyebrow mb-3","children":["What we see in ","Downtown Nashville"]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-3xl lg:text-4xl text-ink mb-7 leading-tight","children":["The plumbing reality of ","Downtown Nashville","."]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"prose-editorial","children":["$","p",null,{"children":"Downtown Nashville's mix of pre-war buildings (Church Street, Union Street, Printer's Alley), mid-century office towers, and post-2010 high-rise construction (The Gulch, SoBro) means commercial plumbers here have to handle the full range — gravity steam systems in 100-year-old buildings, conventional commercial boilers and tank water heaters in mid-century inventory, and modern condensing units and recirculation systems in the new towers. Restaurants are the other big downtown category for us: high-volume grease management, commercial dishwasher hot water demand, and FOG (fats/oils/grease) compliance with Metro Water are routine work. We do new build-outs, tenant fit-outs, and emergency response across the downtown core."}]}]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"bg-bone-100/60 border-y border-ink/10 py-16 lg:py-24","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"eyebrow mb-3","children":["Downtown Nashville"," plumbing patterns"]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"fon